Title: Core Flow Diagram
Describe: Each main-loop round injects external events, budgets context, calls the model, executes tools, and feeds results back to the model.
------------------------------------------------------------
[Example]
S05_CORE_FLOW: agent_loop main path

[Description]
`agent_loop(messages, context)` lives at `agents/s20_comprehensive.py:1901-2004`.

It first consumes cron jobs and background notifications, optionally injects a todo reminder, prepares context, updates dynamic context, rebuilds the tool pool, and calls the model.

If the model returns no tool use, it triggers the Stop hook and returns.

If the model returns tools, the loop handles explicit compaction, permission hooks, background execution, synchronous handlers, and user-side tool_result feedback.

[UML]
@startuml
start
:Consume cron_queue and inject scheduled prompts;
:Inject completed background notifications;
if (rounds_since_todo is three or more?) then (yes)
  :Append todo reminder;
endif
:prepare_context mutates messages in place;
:update_context and assemble_tool_pool;
:call_llm through with_retry;
if (exception?) then (prompt too long first time)
  :reactive_compact;
  :restart loop;
else (other exception)
  :Append assistant error;
  stop
endif
if (stop_reason is max_tokens?) then (yes)
  if (not escalated yet?) then (yes)
    :Raise max_tokens to 16000;
    :retry model call;
  else (already escalated)
    :Append continuation prompt or return;
  endif
endif
:Append assistant response;
if (no tool_use?) then (yes)
  :trigger Stop hook;
  stop
endif
while (for each tool_use block)
  if (block.name is compact?) then (yes)
    :compact_history;
    :restart loop;
  elseif (PreToolUse blocks?) then (yes)
    :Append denied tool_result;
  elseif (should_run_background?) then (yes)
    :start_background_task;
    :Append placeholder tool_result;
  else (synchronous)
    :call_tool_handler;
    :trigger PostToolUse hook;
  endif
endwhile
:build_user_content and append results;
repeat
@enduml

[Detail]
This activity diagram answers how one `agent_loop` cycle progresses and which branches alter control flow.

Key branches include reactive compaction for prompt-too-long errors, one max-token escalation, explicit `compact` tool handling, permission denial, and background execution.

The arrows represent control flow rather than thread boundaries.

Maintainers should ensure any new branch either appends a valid `tool_result`, restarts intentionally, or returns clearly; otherwise the model may lose feedback for a tool_use block.

------------------------------------------------------------
[Example]
Error recovery and fallback path

[Description]
`with_retry` backs off for 429 rate limits and tracks 529/overloaded failures, switching to `FALLBACK_MODEL_ID` after `MAX_CONSECUTIVE_529` when configured.

`is_prompt_too_long_error` detects prompt or context overflow; `agent_loop` permits one reactive compact for that class of error.

`response.stop_reason == "max_tokens"` first increases output tokens, then allows limited continuation prompts through `MAX_RECOVERY_RETRIES`.

[UML]
None

[Detail]
The recovery paths cover API rate limiting, API overload, prompt/context length, and output truncation.

`RecoveryState` is created per `agent_loop` invocation, so recovery counters are not persisted between sessions or independent loop calls.

That choice is acceptable for a lesson, but production code would usually need more precise error classification, telemetry, and configurable retry/backoff policy.
